PageV06P424
# @COMMENT: According to Khaṭīb al-Baghdādī (d. 463), he was one of the memorizers of *ḥadīth* who traveled in search of new traditions. Ibn Isḥāq is not listed in the *Taʾrīkh Baghdād* as relating to him. He was born in 228 and began to write traditions down at in the year 239 (KHTGV16P341A), writing 5 or 6 volumes. Since Ibn Isḥāq died at the latest in 159 there is no way Yaḥyā b. Ṣāʿid could have related directly from him. Where listed as relating from Ibn Isḥāq, there must be a link or two missing. He is not listed by Khaṭīb as relating from any of Ibn Isḥāq’s witnesses. According to Ibn ʿAsākir, he did hear from Saʿīd b. Yaḥyā b. Saʿīd al-Umawī, the son of the witness Yaḥyā b. Saʿīd al-Umawī (WYSAU) in Iraq (TDSHV64P357A). There is reason to think that the Ibn Isḥāq listed in HJRTV06P424B is actually Muḥammad b. Isḥāq b. Khuzaymah (see, for instance, TLBXV07P3373B). In the *isnād*  found in HJRTV06P424B that lists Ibn Isḥāq as relating to Yaḥyā b. Ṣāʿid, Ibn Isḥāq’s source was ʿAbd Allāh b. Yūsuf al-Tunīsī, who was not one of our Ibn Isḥāq’s sources. The other possible source listed, is Ibn Abī Farwah, or Isḥāq b. Abī Farwah who could be one of several individuals, is not listed anywhere as a source for Ibn Isḥāq. In the above passage, and also in DRQSV02P099C, BQSXV02P234C, and BQQXV01P056C,  Ibn Ṣāʿid is listed as relating from ʿUbayd Allāh b. Saʿd, the grandson of WSACD. It is therefore possible that there are several links between Ibn Isḥāq and Ibn Ṣāʿid.  It is this lack of clarity that Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī seeks to clarify. @EC_01/02/24@

